entry.title: media: Remove stable.mojom.VideoFrame traits.
entry.content:
This CL removes the mojo traits which map stable.mojom.VideoFrame to

scoped_refptr<::media::VideoFrame>. This is in preparation to CL:4457504

which allows the OOPVideoDecoder to re-use frames previously received

from the remote decoder. Removing the traits is useful because with that

CL, not every incoming stable.mojom.VideoFrame received by the

OOPVideoDecoder will result in a media::VideoFrame, and creating a

media::VideoFrame from said stable.mojom.VideoFrame incurs in some

overhead such as consuming a strictly incrementing counter [1] and

validating the underlying GpuMemoryBufferHandle [2].



This CL moves the validation of the incoming stable.mojom.VideoFrame

from the mojo traits to the OOPVideoDecoder which is the only component

that receives them.



Functionally, this CL doesn't change much: we still create a

media::VideoFrame for every incoming stable.mojom.VideoFrame. The actual

re-use of frames is implemented in CL:4457504.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:media/base/video_frame.cc;l=1422;drc=269a0caf81464f39a3d54942a891652ba1f2ba40

[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:media/mojo/mojom/stable/stable_video_decoder_types_mojom_traits.cc;l=1679-1682;drc=bd1cbddfe3cbecc083674c0c9de89b2e67b2cc04

entry.title: IPH [2]: Implement ChainedBackNavigationTracker
entry.content:
This CL creates `chrome::ChainedBackNavigationTracker` that contains

a set of methods to help to record the number of chained back

navigations.



If two history navigation is performed one after another, and the

interval between them is smaller than the threshold, they are

considered chained, and the chain length is 2. The chain is broken

if the interval between two navigations is too long, or there is any

non history navigation in between.



Please refer to the linked doc for more context.

entry.title: [Extensions] Include context type with mojom::RequestParams
entry.content:
Include a specified context type along with the mojom::RequestParams

for an extension API call. This is not to be used as a strong

security boundary, but allows us to differentiate between different

contexts in a given renderer.



This includes multiple steps:

1) Introduce a new mojo type for a context type, mirroring

Feature::Context.

2) Expand mojom::RequestParams to include a renderer-provided

context type and send it along with the request.

3) Most importantly: Update the receiver of the request on the browser

side to look at this context type and validate whether it is allowed

for the given process, rather than trying to determine the most

likely context type from browser-side data about the sender. This

involves introducing a new method,

ProcessMap::CanProcessHostContextType().



More notes on 3):

This should strictly improve security.



We are not relaxing any browser-side security checks we had in place

previously; we are still requiring that any provided context type meets

the browser-side validation (such as requiring that privileged extension

contexts are running in an extension process).



We are adding a few new validations to strengthen these checks, such as

not counting extension content scripts running in webui as webui (this

can only happen with component extensions like ChromeVox and with

special commandline flags).



This allows us to differentiate between different possible contexts

within the same renderer, such as privileged extension contexts and

offscreen documents. In the case of a compromised renderer, this is

no better (and no worse), but in the normal case, this allows us to

properly restrict APIs on the browser side.



This also sets us up to expand validation of these context types, such

as by checking the content script tracker if the renderer claims a

message came from a content script.



Add testing for the new ProcessMap method, ensuring contexts are

properly classified.

entry.title: Set target framerate using a Video control message
entry.content:
The current implementation uses SDP format parameters to adjust

the framerate. This works well for VP8 and VP9 but is not the

supported way of adjusting the AV1 framerate and isn't possible

for H.264. Also we've seen that other browsers occasionally

mangle the SDP (or even set their own max-fr values) which further

complicates this logic.



I'd like to have a consistent way to set the target framerate for

the host, one which will work regardless of the currently

selected encoder so my new approach is to use a control message.



I will likely extend this in the future to control the encoder

speed as well though that is not in scope for this CL.

entry.title: Fix manual testing importer.
entry.content:
Originally, the manual testing importer only supported importing

AutofillProfiles from a JSON file. crrev.com/c/4401107 added support

for credit cards. The intention was that importing should fail if

neither a "profiles" nor a "credit-cards" key specified in the JSON.

However, due to a bug both are currently required:

- DataModelsFromJSON(json_array) receives the "profiles" or

"credit-cards" array extracted from the JSON. It returns an optional

vector of Ts. nullopt means that parsing failed.

If no key was specified and json_array is null, the intention was to

return an empty vector, indicating that parsing trivially succeeded.

- Later, in SetData(), it is verified that parsing of profiles and

credit cards did not fail using CHECK(...profiles.has_value() && ...

credit_cards.has_value()).



The bug is caused by the "return an empty vector":

absl::optional> DataModelsFromJSON(

const base::Value::List* const json_array, ...) {

if (!json_array) {

return {};

}

...

}

Here, "return {}" doesn't return an empty vector, but a default

initialized absl::optional<>. It has value absl::nullopt.

As a result, both a "profiles" and a "credit-cards" key is required.



This CL fixes the problem by explicitly returning a vector.

entry.title: Use a 3-value LoadingState enum to represent loading in content/browser/
entry.content:
Doc: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1m3icCIvVQ2_fEJxzSToAmOiJSyhm_THYHee5lw5Ezoo/edit?usp=sharing



Currently, we track whether loading is in progress as a boolean, but

when we start loading. This CL represents loading state internally

as a 3-state enum (NONE, LOADING_WITHOUT_UI, and LOADING_UI_REQUESTED). It also decouples the callbacks provided by the content/public API.

Right now, WebContentsDelegate::LoadingStateChanged() is always paired

with either a WebContentsObserver::DidStartLoading() or a

WebContentsObserver::DidStopLoading(), which means that the decision

to show loading UI can only be made at load start. Now,

LoadingStateChanged() can also be called separately when the internal loading state of the FrameTree changes between LOADING_WITHOUT_UI and

LOADING_UI_REQUESTED.



This fixes an uncommon case where loading UI could be omitted if an

iframe navigated, then the top frame started navigating before the

iframe finished. It will also enable better loading UI integration

for the web-exposed Navigation API in a follow-up CL.

call to WillDisplayMediaCapturePermissionPrompt. crrev.com/c/4409744

can also be destroyed at this point, since CRWWKUIHandler is indirectly

owned by the WebState. This CL guards against this using a pointer

to `self` declared with objc_precise_lifetime, which prevents

the instance from getting destroyed within the method.

entry.title: [ODPPC] Explicitly set the trigger_notification.. field on issues
entry.content:
For now, all places in Chrome which compute password issues set this

field to false. In order to avoid an large change, the

InsecurityMetadata constructor had a default trigger_notification

param.



As of now, the trigger_notification field is only set to true outside of

Chrome (e.g. by the proactive check on Android). Chrome only which syncs

it down and persists it as-is. (That change was made in

https://crrev.com/c/4414899).



In order to prevent that this field is reset accidentally in the

future, all places should set it explicitly.
